<%@page contentType="text/html" pageEncoding="UTF-8"%>
<%@taglib prefix="t" tagdir="/WEB-INF/tags" %>

<t:genericpage>
	<jsp:attribute name="content">
		<div class="row about-tiles">
			<div class="col-md-4 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
		
				<div class="box box-solid bg-blue-gradient">
					<div class="box-header">
						<i class="fa fa-globe"></i>
						<h3 class="box-title">The Best of the Web</h3>
					</div>
					<div class="box-body">
						<p>
							We have automatically scraped the web to aggregate all of the resources from different sources into one resource that is easy to use,
							and well organized. No need to keep searching for the answer to your question in different places. If the answer isn't on this site,
							it probably doesn't exist yet. Contribute to the site by expanding the amount of information available on the web!
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
		
				<div class="box box-solid bg-purple-gradient">
					<div class="box-header">
						<i class="fa fa-bar-chart-o"></i>
						<h3 class="box-title">Curated Resources</h3>
					</div>
					<div class="box-body">
						<p>
							Our database of millions of calculus questions adaptively customizes itself to your needs.
							When you rate a problem, you provide feedback on how you learn, and allow us to provide better resources in the future.
							This system of user driven product feedback is what makes Calcu.us successful, and allows it to become better over time.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
		
				<div class="box box-solid bg-black-gradient">
					<div class="box-header">
						<i class="fa fa-money"></i>
						<h3 class="box-title">Free. Always.</h3>
					</div>
					<div class="box-body">
						<p>
							Calcu.us is free to use.  Always.  We don't sell memberships, we don't sell ads, and we don't preference any user over another.
							Ever.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
		
			</div>
		
			<div class="col-md-4 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
		
				<div class="box box-solid bg-green-gradient">
					<div class="box-header">
						<i class="fa fa-group"></i>
						<h3 class="box-title">Vibrant Community</h3>
					</div>
					<div class="box-body">
						<p>
							A unique community of users constructs problems, finds solutions, asks questions, and provides feedback.
							This community continues to grow the amount of information that we have access to and understanding of,
							and is at the heart of the development of new features, contenta, and ideas.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
		
				<div class="box box-solid bg-maroon-gradient">
					<div class="box-header">
						<i class="fa fa-flask"></i>
						<h3 class="box-title">Research</h3>
					</div>
					<div class="box-body">
						<p>
							Calcu.us also has the goal of becoming a site where researchers can conduct anonymous studies of how learners learn,
							and how we can develop better software to meet the needs of learners. By using the site, you are contributing to
							one of the largest scientific studies on learning techniques ever conducted!
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
		
				<div class="box box-solid bg-light-blue-gradient">
					<div class="box-header">
						<i class="fa fa-plane"></i>
						<h3 class="box-title">Directed Resources</h3>
					</div>
					<div class="box-body">
						<p>
							Whether you rock that practice problem, or found it a bit too difficult, CalcU.us will recommend other resources to check out,
							based on your profile and your history with similar problems.  This system can quickly figure out where you are, and how to help
							you get to a greater level of understanding.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
		
			</div>
		
			<div class="col-md-4 col-sm-12 col-xs-12">
				<div class="row">
		
					<div class="col-md-12 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
						<div class="box box-solid bg-yellow-gradient">
							<div class="box-header">
								<i class="fa fa-trophy"></i>
								<h3 class="box-title">Karma Reimagined</h3>
							</div>
							<div class="box-body">
								<p>
									When you contribute on Calcu.us, whether through asking questions, answering them, creating content or practice problems, or just
									regualrly using and rating things on the site, we reward your contributions through the gift of Karma!  Karma can be spent in a
									couple of cool ways, including broadcasting a message to all the users on the site!  For more information, check out our achievments
									page.
								</p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
		
					<div class="col-md-12 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
						<div class="box box-solid bg-aqua-gradient">
							<div class="box-header">
								<i class="fa fa-lock"></i>
								<h3 class="box-title">Privacy</h3>
							</div>
							<div class="box-body">
								<p>
									We pledge to NEVER distribute or sell any of your identifying information.  All studies which use the datasets that we cultivate will adhere to the strictest
									set of anonymity guidelines possible.
								</p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
		
					<div class="col-md-12 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
						<div class="box box-solid bg-red-gradient">
							<div class="box-header">
								<i class="fa fa-heart"></i>
								<h3 class="box-title">Born in Boston</h3>
							</div>
							<div class="box-body">
								<p>
									calcu.us is a simple idea that was started at Brandeis University in Boston.  It was made by an optimistic undergrad with the sole goal of making
									learning calculus easier. To get involved in the project, to contribute comentary or feedback, please reach out by checking out our contact page.
								</p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
		
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="about-author box box-solid">
			<div class="box-header">
				<i class="fa fa-user"></i>
				<h3 class="box-title">About the Author</h3>
			</div>
			<div class="box-body">
				Grady Ward is a student at Brandeis University who is excited about the role of technology in the future of education.
				If he is not running, programming, teaching, eating, drinking or sleeping, please get him to the nearest doctor.
				His passions include lego star wars, Edward Elgar, French Rap, and wikipedia articles about physics.
				In the last four years, he has cried twice: Brokeback Mountain, and at a piece of origami at the Boston MFA.
				His role model is the desk, as it is always up for work, but is often not used for it.
			</div>
		</div>
	</jsp:attribute>
</t:genericpage>